  volume = {2015},
  number = {1},
  pages = {746},
  publisher = {Environmental Health Perspectives},
  doi = {10.1289/isee.2015.2015-746},
  urldate = {2025-06-25},
  abstract = {Introduction: Dengue dynamics are driven by complex interactions between hosts, vectors and viruses that are influenced by environmental and climatic factors. El Ni{\~n}o Southern Oscillation (ENSO) is a multiyear climate driver of local temperature and rainfall worldwide while the Indian Ocean Dipole (IOD) is a coupled ocean-atmosphere phenomenon in the Indian Ocean which controls the summer monsoon rainfall in the Indian region. Several studies examined the role of El Ni{\~n}o Southern Oscillation (ENSO) in dengue incidence. However, the role of IOD remains unexplored. Here, we examined the effects of ENSO and IOD on dengue incidence in Bangladesh. Methods: Distributed lag nonlinear model and wavelet coherence analysis were performed to estimate the association between the monthly dengue incidence in Bangladesh (January 2000-October 2012), ENSO index (Nino 3.4, a measure of the average sea surface temperature in the Nino 3.4 region) and IOD index (DMI- dipole mode index). Results: Both ENSO and IOD were positively associated with dengue incidence in Bangladesh. A unit increase in ENSO and IOD was associated with an increase of 3.3\% (95\% confidence interval (CI): 0.8, 12.3) and 2.5\% (95\% CI: 0.5, 11.7) in dengue incidence, respectively. There was a strong coherence between ENSO and dengue at a periodicity of 1-2 years, when the coherence between IOD and dengue was observed at a periodicity of 1 year. Conclusions: The findings of this study suggest that both ENSO and IOD play an important role in dengue transmission and should be taken into account when building predictive models for dengue in Bangladesh. The results of this study may provide an empirical basis for predicting dengue epidemics in Bangladesh and have potential to improve disease control in vulnerable regions.}
}

